BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Northwestern": "https://www.music.northwestern.edu/events/amanda-majeski-vocal-master-class-0?eventdate=1775606400"}
X-SOURCE-ID:northwestern
SUMMARY:Amanda Majeski Vocal Master Class
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T000000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T020000Z
UID:303abbc1bc9734158f815dd2f7e43d6f@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:Part of the Tichio-Finnie Vocal Master Class Series \nLurdes 
 Zapata and Maya Behiri\, soprano\; Isabel Yang\, mezzo-soprano\; Leonardo 
 Mangalindan\, tenor\; Alan Darling\, piano \n\nThe Financial Times remark
 ed that soprano Amanda Majeski’s (‘06) “well-rounded soprano... is s
 o warm and glorious\, the singing so outstanding\, that she leaves no emot
 ions unstirred.” A celebrated interpreter of Mozart\, Strauss\, Wagner\,
  and Handel\, Majeski is acclaimed for her portrayal of the title role in 
 Janáček’s Káťa Kabanová\, which she debuted at the Royal Opera Hous
 e\, Covent Garden in 2019. Prior to that performance\, she made her Metrop
 olitan Opera debut as Countess Almaviva in a 2014 production of Le nozze d
 i Figaro and reprised the role for her mainstage debut at the Lyric Opera 
 of Chicago on just a few hours’ notice. Her 2025-26 season began with he
 r debut in the title role of Shostakovich’s Lady Macbeth of Mtsensk at t
 he BBC Proms and includes a return to Oper Frankfurt as Marta in The Passe
 nger\, as well as appearances as the Marschallin in Der Rosenkavalier with
  New Orleans Opera and engagements with the Rundfunk-Sinfonieorchester Ber
 lin for Szymanowski’s Stabat Mater and Mahler’s Fourth Symphony. In th
 is master class\, she coaches accomplished Bienen School voice and opera s
 tudents.
LOCATION:Patrick G. and Shirley W. Ryan Center for the Musical Arts\, 70 A
 rts Circle\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://www.music.northwestern.edu/events/amanda-majeski-vocal-master-
 class-0?eventdate=1775606400
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Northwestern": "https://planitpurple.northwestern.edu/event/639971"}
X-SOURCE-ID:northwestern
SUMMARY:Strategic Storytelling: Nonfiction & Narrative | Sexual Assault Ac
 tion Month
DTSTART;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T000000Z
DTEND;TZID=UTC;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260408T013000Z
UID:d02d5bbccdb8647f530e44bab2dac388@northwestern.edu
DESCRIPTION:For many survivors of interpersonal violence\, telling their s
 tory can be a crucial part of the healing journey. Being honest and vulner
 able in nonfiction writing can be a powerful experience\, but it can prese
 nt its own set of challenges\, especially if that writing is shared with t
 he world. This workshop will explore the many avenues that survivors may c
 hoose to explore their experiences through narrative nonfiction writing\, 
 offer prompts for reflection and self-compassion when sharing stories of h
 arm\, discuss how survivors can maintain their safety and well-being when 
 sharing their stories\, and hold space for free writing.  \n4/7 7:00pm Wo
 men’s Center  | Food provided | RSVP Required
LOCATION:Women's Center\, 2000 Sheridan Rd.\, Evanston\, IL
URL:https://planitpurple.northwestern.edu/event/639971
X-SOURCE:Northwestern University
END:VEVENT
